english:
  title: Preface to the Exemplars of Statecraft and Literature
  author: Jeong Dojeon
  language: eng
  text: |
    The Exemplars of Statecraft and Literature is a work authored by Minister of the Three Departments, the Earl of Bonghwa, Lord Jeong. From his youth, he delighted in learning and pursued profound understanding of the classics, harboring exceptional talent and holding fast to the Way. Thus he harbored great aspirations to govern the world. When our sovereign received the Mandate and rose to power, the Lord resolved uncertainties and devised strategies, becoming a founding merit-subject. Combining the accomplishments of both civil and military arts, he undertook the responsibilities of both general and minister. In all matters of state governance, he invariably drew upon ancient precedent, weighing them against the exigencies of the present. He promoted what was beneficial and eliminated what was harmful, and the people received his blessings. This is governance in its greatest measure.

    In surveying the ancients, he extensively gathered the successes and failures of officials throughout the dynasties past, and assessed both the virtuous and the unworthy among men, committing these to writing. Though he cited the words of former sages, he occasionally appended his own observations without explicit distinction. His writing is concise without omission, detailed without excess—a work that instructs and warns alike. It teaches all who hold office to recognize that their responsibilities are no light matter, and thereby encourages them to diligently fulfill their duties. Its benefit to the world is indeed profound.

    Observing this work, I note it begins with the office of Prime Minister, for that position bears the heaviest responsibility. Through it one discusses the Way and orders the realm, regulating the harmony of heaven and earth. No other office compares in weight and consequence. How few among the ancients truly fulfilled this role! Before the Three Dynasties, we remember Kui, Gao Yao, Hou Ji, Xie, Yi Yin, Lu Fu, the Duke of Zhou, and the Duke of Shao. After the Three Dynasties, we find Xiao He and Cao Can of Han; Bing Ji and Wei Xiang; Fang Xuanling, Du Ruhui, Yao Seng, and Song Jing of Tang; and Han Qi, Fu Bi, Wang Anshi, Fan Zhongluo, and Sima Guang of Song—a mere handful of names. Ah, is not the office of Prime Minister exceedingly difficult?

    Therefore, a ruler must make the selection of his prime minister his first priority, and one who serves as prime minister must constantly consider how to fulfill his office worthily. Following this come the remonstrating officials—the censorate to expose and prevent corruption of custom, the remonstrators to speak truth to the ruler's failings. These are positions of great importance to the state. Can those who hold such offices simply acquiesce and drift, abandoning their duties? Furthermore, the military forces require constant training and cultivation; when necessity calls, they must stand firm against disorder in times of crisis. This must never be taken lightly. The provincial inspector must keep the land clean and clear, punishing the powerful and cunning while redressing the grievances of the oppressed and nurturing worthy talent. This office demands utmost care. The provincial governors, prefects, and county magistrates are those through whom the ruler governs. When such officials are virtuous, the people flourish; when they lack virtue, the people suffer. How then could one carelessly appoint unworthy persons to these posts? This is why they are recorded in succession.

    Should one become a military commander, a provincial inspector, or a local magistrate, how could one fail to consider how to fulfill one's office? The essentials of governance do not exceed these few positions. If each official truly fulfills his responsibility, then governing all under heaven becomes no difficult matter—how much less a single realm! In this we perceive that Lord Jeong's learning has deep roots and his talents are suited to their application.

    A visitor once said to me: "Generally, those ancients who wrote books did so because they harbored ambitions they could not fulfill through action. Yet Lord Jeong met a sage ruler and attained the rank of Prime Minister. He cannot say he lacked opportunity, nor that the Way remains unexecuted. Why then write a book?" I replied: "Lord Jeong's heart desires nothing less than to make ruler and people equal to those of Yao and Shun. If even the slightest aspect of the Way remains unfulfilled in his practice, his spirit harbors an incompleteness. This, I believe, is why he composed this work."
  footnotes:
    - The Exemplars of Statecraft and Literature (經濟文鑑) was written by Jeong Dojeon (정도전, 1342–1398), a founding figure of Joseon. The sealer held the title Earl of Bonghwa (奉化伯) and served as a Minister of the Three Departments (判三司事).
    - This preface was written by another important Joseon statesman, likely as an endorsement of Jeong Dojeon's work on proper governance.
    - The reference to 'Yao and Shun' invokes the legendary sage-kings of ancient China, representing the ideal of virtuous rulership sought in Confucian governance.
